[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] The Notifications API allows web pages to control the display of system notifications to the end user.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] A web notification is a message box used to inform users when events occur on web apps.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Web notifications are rendered by the operating system's native notification system, making them display identically to notifications from any other app on the platform.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Because the underlying OS renders web notifications, they are outside the top-level browsing context viewport, and can be shown even when the user has switched tabs or moved to a different app.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] In order to use notifications, the user needs to grant the current origin permission to display system notifications.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] This is generally done when the app or site initializes, using the `Notification.requestPermission()` method.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] This method should only be called when handling a user gesture, such as when handling a mouse click.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] (A dialog box asking the user to allow notifications from that origin.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] From here the user can choose to allow notifications from this origin, or block them.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Once a choice has been made, the setting will generally persist for the current session.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Notifications are created using the `Notification()` constructor.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] This must be passed a title argument, and can optionally be passed a parameter to specify options such as text direction, body text, icon to display, notification sound to play, and more.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] For example, the following code shows how you might create a notification that sets the `navigate` option, specifying a URL that will be opened if the notification is accepted (you can also define click handlers to process notification actions).
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] For more usage examples see Using the Notifications API.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] When activated, a non-persistent notification fires a `click` event, unless a `navigate` URL is set, in which case the user agent navigates to that URL instead.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Represents a notification event dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Occurs when a user clicks on a displayed persistent notification, unless a `navigate` URL is set.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Occurs when a user closes a displayed notification.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Returns a list of the notifications in the order that they were created from the current origin via the current service worker registration.
[src:notifications-api/notifications-api] Displays the notification with the requested title.
[src:notifications-api/permission-static] The **`permission`** read-only static property of the `Notification` interface indicates the current permission granted by the user for the current origin to display web notifications.
[src:notifications-api/permission-static] A string representing the current permission.
[src:notifications-api/permission-static] The user has explicitly granted permission for the current origin to display system notifications.
[src:notifications-api/permission-static] The user has explicitly denied permission for the current origin to display system notifications.
[src:notifications-api/permission-static] The user decision is unknown; in this case the application will act as if permission was `denied`.
