[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Desktop notifications usually disappear automatically after a short amount of time.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Often their content is then stored in some widget that allows the users to access past notifications at a more convenient time.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] On mobile devices, a push notification system is typically used.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] In Windows 2000, Microsoft introduced balloon help-like passive pop-up notifications, tied to the notification area of the taskbar.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Notifications get queued when user is away or screensaver is running, and get shown when the user resumes activity.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] They remain on screen for nine seconds while fading out if the user appears to ignore them.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Microsoft also adopted similar notifications for its other software such as Windows Phone using the Microsoft Push Notification Service, Internet Explorer 7 and later, Microsoft Outlook, Microsoft Security Essentials, as well as Windows 8 and Windows 10 using the Windows Notification Service.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Desktop notifications are a proposed standard for freedesktop.org, but all the major desktop environments running on the X Window System already support this standard, making them typically available on Linux and other Unix-like systems.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Google adopted the concepts of notification drawer and toast popup messages for user notifications as basic components of its Android operating system.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] macOS (since OS X Mountain Lion) provides desktop notifications via Notification Center.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Previous versions of OS X have no built-in desktop notification feature; however, Growl is a popular application that provides similar functionality and enjoys broad support from third-party software. iOS also includes Notification Center as of iOS 5.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Browsers that support JavaScript typically implement the Notification API.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] This API asks for user confirmation to allow popups and give the programmer the opportunity to display notifications with a text (body) along with a descriptive icon and header.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] While passive pop-ups do not require any user interaction, some implementations still provide a way for the user to optionally interact with the pop-up.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] For the Freedesktop specification, this is an optional feature that clients cannot rely on, and its use is discouraged by some design guidelines.
[src:notifications-api/pop-up-notification] Android adds the ability to provide actions with Jelly Bean.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The Notifications API lets a web page or app send notifications that are displayed outside the page at the system level; this lets web apps send information to a user even if the application is idle or in the background.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] This article looks at the basics of using this API in your own apps.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Typically, system notifications refer to the operating system's standard notification mechanism: think for example of how a typical desktop system or mobile device broadcasts notifications.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] (Desktop notification: To do list via mdn.github.io HEY!
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The system notification system will vary of course by platform and browser, but this is OK, and the Notifications API is written to be general enough for compatibility with most system notification systems.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] One of the most obvious use cases for web notifications is a web-based mail or IRC application that needs to notify the user when a new message is received, even if the user is doing something else with another application.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Many examples of this now exist, such as Slack.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] We've written a real-world example — a to-do list app — to give more of an idea of how web notifications can be used.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] It stores data locally using IndexedDB and notifies users when tasks are due using system notifications.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Download the To-do list code, or view the app running live.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Before an app can send a notification, the user must grant the application the right to do so.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] This is a common requirement when an API tries to interact with something outside a web page — at least once, the user needs to specifically grant that application permission to present notifications, thereby letting the user control which apps/sites are allowed to display notifications.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Because of abuses of push notifications in the past, web browsers and developers have begun to implement strategies to help mitigate this problem.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] You should only request consent to display notifications in response to a user gesture (e.g., clicking a button).
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] This is not only best practice — you should not be spamming users with notifications they didn't agree to — but going forward browsers will explicitly disallow notification permission requests not triggered in response to a user gesture.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Firefox is already doing this from version 72, for example, and Safari has done it for some time.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] In addition, In Chrome and Firefox you cannot request notifications at all unless the site is a secure context (i.e., HTTPS), and you can no longer allow notification permissions to be requested from cross-origin `<iframe>`s.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] You can check to see if you already have permission by checking the value of the `Notification.permission` read only property.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The user hasn't been asked for permission yet, so notifications won't be displayed.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The user has granted permission to display notifications, after having been asked previously.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The user has explicitly declined permission to show notifications.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] If permission to display notifications hasn't been granted yet, the application needs to use the `Notification.requestPermission()` method to request this from the user.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] This uses the promise-based version of the method.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The callback version optionally accepts a callback function that is called once the user has responded to the request to display permissions.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] In our todo list demo, we include an "Enable notifications" button that, when pressed, requests notification permissions for the app.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Looking at the second main block first, you'll see that we first check to see if Notifications are supported.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] If they are, we run the promise-based version of `Notification.requestPermission()`, and if not, we log a message to the console.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Inside the promise resolution handler passed to `then`, we show or hide the button depending on what the user chose in the permission dialog.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] We don't want to show it if permission has already been granted, but if the user chose to deny permission, we want to give them the chance to change their mind later on.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Creating a notification is easy; just use the `Notification` constructor.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] This constructor expects a title to display within the notification and some options to enhance the notification such as an `icon` or a text `body`.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Use `close()` to remove a notification that is no longer relevant to the user (e.g., the user already read the notification on the webpage, in the case of a messaging app, or the following song is already playing in a music app to notifies upon song changes).
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Most modern browsers dismiss notifications automatically after a few moments (around four seconds) but this isn't something you should generally be concerned about as it's up to the user and user agent.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] The dismissal may also happen at the operating system level and users should remain in control of this.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Old versions of Chrome didn't remove notifications automatically so you can do so after a `setTimeout()` only for those legacy versions in order to not remove notifications from notification trays on other browsers.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Triggered when the user clicks on the notification.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Triggered once the notification is closed.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Triggered if something goes wrong with the notification; this is usually because the notification couldn't be displayed for some reason.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Triggered when the notification is displayed to the user.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] These events can be tracked using the `onclick`, `onclose`, `onerror`, and `onshow` handlers.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Because `Notification` also inherits from `EventTarget`, it's possible to use the `addEventListener()` method on it.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] Instead of handling click events, you can set the `navigate` option to automatically open a URL when the user activates the notification.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] This bypasses both the `click` and `notificationclick` events.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] See `Notification.navigate` for details.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] It is usually undesirable for a user to receive a lot of notifications in a short space of time — for example, what if a messenger application notified a user for each incoming message, and they were being sent a lot?
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] To avoid spamming the user with too many notifications, it's possible to modify the pending notifications queue, replacing single or multiple pending notifications with a new one.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] To do this, it's possible to add a tag to any new notification.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] If a notification already has the same tag and has not been displayed yet, the new notification replaces that previous notification.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] If the notification with the same tag has already been displayed, the previous notification is closed and the new one is displayed.
[src:notifications-api/using-the-notifications-api] To test the above example, change the send notification setting for the `https://live.mdnplay.dev` website.
